          <b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/0-4049">marco.m.morana</a></b>
          <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">7 days ago<span>
        </div>
      </td>
      <td valign="top" align="right">
      <div id="CommentBar_1649" style="display:none;">

      
      <span id="FlagComment_1649">
        <a class="iconLink" href="javascript:ajaxLink('FlagComment_1649', '/akira/flagDiscussionComment.do?topicID=2595&commentID=1649')"><img alt="Warning" class="iconLink" src="/images/iconshock/warning_16.gif" border="0">&nbsp;Report Abuse</a>
      </span>
      


            


      </div>
      </td>
    </tr>
    </table>

      


      I think is a good idea for both citizens and the government. For US citizens/taxpayers, it allows monitoring of PII data breaches and for the US government for informed risk management decisions.<br/>Some data can be already aggregated from available data sources such as: <br/>Privacy Rights Clearinghouse http://www.privacyrights.org/ar/ChronDataBreaches.htm<br/><br/>Attrition.org statistics on data loss:<br/>http://attrition.org/dataloss/<br/><br/>FTC<br/>http://www.ftc.gov/os/2007/11/SynovateFinalReportIDTheft2006.pdf<br/><br/>Regards<br/><br/>Marco

                  
